{
  "What does percent error measure?": "",
  "How close a measured value is to the accepted (true) value": "",
  "How many mistakes were made during data collection overall": "",
  "How many trials were completed during the whole experiment": "",
  "The total number of measurements taken in all lab trials": "",
  "Percent error measures how far a measured (experimental) value is from the accepted (true) value, expressed as a percentage. A lower percent error means a more accurate measurement.": "",
  "What is the formula for percent error?": "",
  "(Accepted − Experimental) ÷ Experimental × 100%": "",
  "|Accepted − Experimental| ÷ Accepted × 100%": "",
  "(Accepted + Experimental) ÷ Accepted × 100%": "",
  "Experimental ÷ Accepted × 100% for all cases": "",
  "Percent error = |Accepted − Experimental| ÷ Accepted × 100%. The absolute value ensures the result is always positive, regardless of whether the measured value is above or below the accepted value.": "",
  "A student measures the boiling point of water as 99°C. The accepted value is 100°C. What is the percent error?": "",
  "10%": "",
  "1%": "",
  "0.1%": "",
  "5%": "",
  "Percent error = |100 − 99| ÷ 100 × 100% = 1 ÷ 100 × 100% = 1%. This is a very small percent error, indicating an accurate measurement.": "",
  "What does a percent error of 0% mean?": "",
  "The experiment completely failed to produce results": "",
  "The measured value is exactly equal to the accepted value": "",
  "No measurements were taken during the experiment run": "",
  "The accepted value for the quantity is currently unknown": "",
  "A percent error of 0% means the experimental measurement matches the accepted value exactly. While rare in practice, it represents perfect accuracy.": "",
  "Which percent error indicates the most accurate measurement?": "",
  "25%": "",
  "50%": "",
  "2%": "",
  "A smaller percent error means greater accuracy. A 2% error means the measurement is very close to the accepted value, while a 50% error means the measurement is far off.": "",
  "Why do we use absolute value in the percent error formula?": "",
  "To ensure the percent error is always a positive number": "",
  "To make the calculation simpler by removing decimals": "",
  "To double the error value for more conservative estimates": "",
  "To convert the accepted value into the correct units": "",
  "Absolute value ensures the percent error is always positive. Whether you measure too high or too low compared to the accepted value, the error is reported as a positive percentage.": "",
  "A student measures the density of aluminum as 2.5 g/cm³. The accepted value is 2.7 g/cm³. What is the percent error?": "",
  "About 7.4%": "",
  "About 8.0%": "",
  "About 2.0%": "",
  "About 5.0%": "",
  "Percent error = |2.7 − 2.5| ÷ 2.7 × 100% = 0.2 ÷ 2.7 × 100% ≈ 7.4%. The student's measurement was about 7.4% away from the accepted density of aluminum.": "",
  "In the percent error formula, which value goes in the denominator?": "",
  "The experimental value": "",
  "The accepted value": "",
  "The average of both values": "",
  "The difference of the values": "",
  "The accepted (true) value goes in the denominator of the percent error formula. This is because we are measuring how far off the experimental value is relative to what the answer should be.": "",
  "A student calculates a percent error of 15%. What does this tell her about her measurement?": "",
  "Her measurement was exactly 15 units away from the accepted value": "",
  "Her measurement was 15% different from the true accepted value": "",
  "She completed only 15% of the required experimental trials": "",
  "Her experiment was 15% more reliable than the previous test": "",
  "A 15% error means her measured value differed from the accepted value by 15%. This is a moderate error that suggests her measurement was somewhat close but could be improved.": "",
  "If the accepted value for the speed of sound is 343 m/s and a student measures 350 m/s, what is the approximate percent error?": "",
  "About 7.0%": "",
  "About 0.2%": "",
  "About 20%": "",
  "Percent error = |343 − 350| ÷ 343 × 100% = 7 ÷ 343 × 100% ≈ 2.0%. This is a good result, showing the student's measurement was quite close to the accepted speed of sound.": "",
  "What is the 'accepted value' in a percent error calculation?": "",
  "The true or standard value determined by scientists and published in references": "",
  "The value that a student measures during a laboratory experiment trial": "",
  "The average of all measurements taken during the experiment by everyone": "",
  "The value that the student predicted before performing the experiment": "",
  "The accepted value (also called the true or theoretical value) is the standard value that has been determined by reliable scientific research and is published in reference materials like textbooks.": "",
  "What is the 'experimental value' in a percent error calculation?": "",
  "The standard value found in a textbook or scientific reference source": "",
  "The value obtained through measurement during an experiment or lab": "",
  "The predicted value written in the hypothesis before any testing begins": "",
  "The value calculated by finding the range of all collected data points": "",
  "The experimental value is the measurement obtained by the experimenter during a lab or investigation. It is compared to the accepted value to calculate how accurate the measurement was.": "",
  "What does 'absolute value' mean in the percent error formula?": "",
  "The distance of a number from zero, which is always positive or zero": "",
  "The exact measured value recorded directly from the instrument used": "",
  "The accepted value that all scientists agree upon as the standard": "",
  "The largest possible value that a measurement could ever reach": "",
  "Absolute value is the distance of a number from zero on the number line, always expressed as a positive number. For example, |−5| = 5 and |5| = 5. In percent error, it ensures the result is never negative.": "",
  "What does 'systematic error' mean?": "",
  "An error that consistently shifts all measurements in the same direction": "",
  "An error that occurs randomly and differently in every single trial": "",
  "An error that only happens during the very first trial of an experiment": "",
  "An error caused by not having enough data points to analyze results": "",
  "A systematic error consistently shifts all measurements in the same direction (always too high or always too low). Examples include a miscalibrated instrument or always reading a meniscus incorrectly.": "",
  "What does 'random error' mean?": "",
  "An error that consistently shifts all measurements in one same direction": "",
  "Unpredictable variations in measurements that scatter results above and below": "",
  "An error caused by intentionally changing the experimental procedure": "",
  "An error that makes the percent error exactly equal to zero every time": "",
  "Random errors are unpredictable fluctuations that cause measurements to scatter above and below the true value. They are caused by factors like slight variations in timing, reading instruments, or environmental conditions.": "",
  "What does 'percent' mean in percent error?": "",
  "A way of expressing a number as a fraction out of one hundred": "",
  "A measurement unit used exclusively for very small quantities": "",
  "A type of mathematical operation similar to multiplication only": "",
  "The number of decimal places used in the final answer value": "",
  "Percent means 'per hundred' or 'out of 100.' Expressing error as a percentage makes it easy to compare the accuracy of different measurements regardless of their units or magnitude.": "",
  "What does 'human error' mean in a lab?": "",
  "Mistakes made by the experimenter, such as misreading instruments or spilling samples": "",
  "Errors that occur only when computers are used to analyze the experimental data": "",
  "The natural variation in measurements that happens even with perfect technique": "",
  "An error that is automatically corrected by repeating the experiment more times": "",
  "Human error refers to mistakes made by the person conducting the experiment. These can include misreading a scale, timing incorrectly, spilling a substance, or recording the wrong number.": "",
  "What does 'calibration error' mean?": "",
  "An error due to an instrument not being properly adjusted or zeroed before use": "",
  "An error that occurs randomly in every measurement taken during the trial": "",
  "An error that only affects the control group in a controlled experiment test": "",
  "An error caused by having too few data points for meaningful analysis": "",
  "A calibration error occurs when a measuring instrument is not properly adjusted or zeroed. For example, a scale that reads 2 grams when empty will add 2 grams to every measurement, causing systematic error.": "",
  "What is 'measurement uncertainty' mean?": "",
  "The range of possible values within which the true measurement likely falls": "",
  "The exact difference between the accepted and experimental values obtained": "",
  "The scientist's personal doubt about whether the experiment is worthwhile": "",
  "The number of significant figures recorded in the final answer of a lab": "",
  "Measurement uncertainty is the range within which the true value likely lies. Every measurement has some uncertainty because no instrument is perfectly precise. For example, a ruler measurement of 5.3 cm might have an uncertainty of ±0.1 cm.": "",
  "What does 'error analysis' mean in science?": "",
  "The process of identifying, calculating, and explaining sources of error in an experiment": "",
  "The process of eliminating all errors so that every measurement is perfectly correct": "",
  "The step of designing a new experiment after the previous one failed completely": "",
  "The process of collecting data before performing any mathematical calculations": "",
  "Error analysis is the process of examining an experiment to identify what caused inaccuracies, calculate how large the errors were, and explain how they affected the results. It is a critical part of lab reports.": "",
  "A student measures the mass of a metal block as 48 g. The accepted mass is 50 g. What is her percent error?": "",
  "4%": "",
  "8%": "",
  "6%": "",
  "Percent error = |50 − 48| ÷ 50 × 100% = 2 ÷ 50 × 100% = 4%. Her measurement was 4% different from the accepted value.": "",
  "A student calculates a percent error of 25% on a density lab. Her lab partner gets 3% on the same experiment. What can you conclude?": "",
  "Both students were equally accurate in their density measurements": "",
  "The lab partner's measurement was much more accurate than the student's result": "",
  "The student's measurement was more accurate because 25 is a larger number": "",
  "Neither measurement can be evaluated without knowing the actual density value": "",
  "A lower percent error means greater accuracy. The lab partner's 3% error means their measurement was much closer to the accepted density value than the student's 25% error.": "",
  "A student measures the acceleration due to gravity as 10.5 m/s². The accepted value is 9.8 m/s². What is the approximate percent error?": "",
  "About 3.6%": "",
  "About 7.1%": "",
  "About 10.5%": "",
  "About 0.7%": "",
  "Percent error = |9.8 − 10.5| ÷ 9.8 × 100% = 0.7 ÷ 9.8 × 100% ≈ 7.1%. The student's measurement was about 7.1% higher than the accepted acceleration due to gravity.": "",
  "A lab group measures the freezing point of water as 2°C instead of 0°C. They notice their thermometer was not zeroed properly. What type of error is this?": "",
  "A random error that affects each trial differently each time": "",
  "A systematic error from a calibration problem with the thermometer": "",
  "A human error from misreading the scale on the thermometer used": "",
  "Not an error at all, since 2°C is close enough to the true value": "",
  "This is a systematic error caused by a calibration problem — the thermometer reads 2°C too high every time. This type of error shifts all measurements in the same direction and does not average out with more trials.": "",
  "A student calculates the density of an object as 8.2 g/cm³. Her textbook says the accepted density of copper is 8.96 g/cm³. Should she conclude her object is probably copper?": "",
  "Yes, because 8.2 and 8.96 are the same when rounded to the nearest whole number": "",
  "Possibly, but she should calculate the percent error to see how close she is": "",
  "No, because any difference at all means the object cannot possibly be copper": "",
  "Yes, because density measurements always have at least 20% error in every lab": "",
  "She should calculate the percent error: |8.96 − 8.2| ÷ 8.96 × 100% ≈ 8.5%. This is moderately close. She may want to refine her measurement technique or consider other possible materials.": "",
  "Two students measure the length of a hallway. The accepted length is 20 meters. Student A gets 19.5 m and Student B gets 22 m. Who has the lower percent error?": "",
  "Student B, because 22 is a larger number and therefore more accurate": "",
  "Student A, because 19.5 m is closer to the accepted value of 20 m": "",
  "Both have the same percent error since they are both near 20 meters": "",
  "Neither can be evaluated because the hallway could be a different length": "",
  "Student A: |20 − 19.5| ÷ 20 × 100% = 2.5%. Student B: |20 − 22| ÷ 20 × 100% = 10%. Student A has the lower percent error (2.5% vs. 10%) and is therefore more accurate.": "",
  "A student performing a lab gets different results each of the 5 times she measures the same quantity: 15.2, 14.8, 15.5, 14.9, 15.1. What type of error is most likely causing the variation?": "",
  "Systematic error shifting all values in one direction only": "",
  "Random error causing measurements to scatter around a value": "",
  "Calibration error making every instrument read incorrectly": "",
  "No error at all because the values are all very close together": "",
  "The measurements scatter both above and below a central value (around 15.1), which is characteristic of random error. Random errors are unpredictable and can be reduced by averaging multiple trials.": "",
  "A student measures the speed of a cart as 2.8 m/s. The accepted value is 3.0 m/s. Her teacher says percent errors below 5% are acceptable. Did she pass the accuracy threshold?": "",
  "No, because her percent error is about 6.7%, which exceeds the 5% threshold": "",
  "Yes, because her percent error is about 2.0%, which is well under the 5% limit": "",
  "Yes, because her percent error is about 3.5%, which is under the 5% threshold": "",
  "No, because her percent error is about 28%, which greatly exceeds the limit": "",
  "Percent error = |3.0 − 2.8| ÷ 3.0 × 100% = 0.2 ÷ 3.0 × 100% ≈ 6.7%. Since 6.7% is above the 5% threshold, she did not meet the accuracy standard.": "",
  "A student finds the volume of a liquid to be 52 mL, but the accepted value is 50 mL. Her partner measures 47 mL. Which student has a smaller percent error, and what is it?": "",
  "The first student with 4% error, which is less than her partner's 6% error": "",
  "The partner with 3% error, which is less than the first student's 4% error": "",
  "Both have the same error because their measurements differ by 5 mL total": "",
  "The partner with 6% error, which is less than the first student's 10% error": "",
  "First student: |50 − 52| ÷ 50 × 100% = 4%. Partner: |50 − 47| ÷ 50 × 100% = 6%. The first student has the smaller percent error (4% vs. 6%), so her measurement is more accurate.": "",
  "A class performs a pendulum experiment. Every group consistently measures the period as 0.1 seconds too long because the stopwatch has a delay. How would fixing this issue affect their percent error?": "",
  "It would have no effect because the stopwatch delay is a random error": "",
  "It would increase the percent error by adding more sources of uncertainty": "",
  "It would decrease the percent error by eliminating a systematic source of error": "",
  "It would only affect the control group's data and not the experimental group": "",
  "The consistent 0.1 s delay is a systematic error that shifts all measurements in the same direction. Fixing it (using a better stopwatch or accounting for the delay) would bring measurements closer to the true value, reducing percent error.": ""
